<article class="post-2 page type-page status-publish hentry" id="post-2">

	<header class="entry-header">

		<h1 class="entry-title">Why?</h1>
	</header><!-- .entry-header -->

	
	<div class="entry-content">

		
<p>13 years old, my mom sat me on the edge of my bed and told me the facts of life. &#8220;Sex is a beautiful thing that happens between a man and a woman, according to God&#8217;s plan. It should only be done inside of a marriage. Any other kind of sex is a sin.&#8221;</p>



<p>I stared at her. She seemed like she was waiting for an answer. &#8220;Okay,&#8221; I said.</p>



<p>&#8220;Remember, if you have any questions at all, you can ask me.&#8221;</p>



<p>Then she left. I did my best to forget the incident and the acute embarrassment that went with it.</p>



<p>Some folks were fortunate enough to have good relationships with their parents where they felt comfortable asking all the questions they needed to ask, and their parents were wise enough to fill in the info they never thought of asking. For millions of others though, they entered adulthood equipped with only the information that they gained from awkward conversations like I had with my mom, or politically-motivated church and school classes, or just the pure, unfiltered internet.</p>



<p>If you&#8217;re a parent reading this, you&#8217;re probably motivated to equip your kid for adulthood with the best information you can provide. You may also feel unqualified for the task.</p>



<p>If you&#8217;re a young adult, you would probably stab your eyes out with needles rather than start a conversation about sex with your parents. But they are one of your most valuable sources of information about the world, and they are also probably the only people on earth who OWE you an explanation &#8211; for why you were born, where you were born, the circumstances of your life, and everything that shaped it before you even arrived.</p>



<p>This site is meant to help you have the awkward conversations. You take turns choosing a category, and a question is presented. It&#8217;s possible the question will be something you may have been too embarrassed to ask about, something you had never though to ask, something that you hoped your child would never ask, something that you&#8217;d both rather not talk about it.</p>



<p>Lean into the awkwardness. Own it, sit with it, and have a conversation. See where it takes you.</p>



<p>Parents, resist the urge to give advice. Tell stories about your actual lived experience. It&#8217;s the most valuable thing you can offer.</p>



<p>Teens, resist the urge to roll your eyes. Listen, and ask follow-up questions about the parts that don&#8217;t make sense. You deserve an explanation.</p>


